Solid game for the price. Surprisingly good character development. No need to put any extra money, especially because you can start grinding early on. I suggest getting maps from shop before Duapnir rings so you can get great materials early on and develop great equipment. Keeps you wanting to play and develop characters by learning classes and abilities. Good gameplay too, legit TBS game. I gave a four to gameplay only because you're supposed to be playing with 15 characters a map and that's way too much. Too many characters to try to use and get SP. You need to make 10 characters from guild asap, 5 for gameplay (some maps you will get surrounded and out numbered) and 5 for dispatches, which you constantly be doing. Buy maps and send dispatches! Battles are still fun and you douse all characters at first then after main wave of battle you only need a few, and SP becomes difficult to gain even with dual Duapnirs. I put in hours of SP/material grinding. Story is good. Has the feel of a playstore game as opposed to how Fire Emblem feels, but it's similar with added elements. Fun game I would love a sequel and for the sequel to have less characters to use during battle and a better upgrade system as opposed to just switching classes. Great job making this game, it's great. I'm at 30 hours of game play and still not finished campaign or sub events, but have all the legendary gear and almost all classes for each character mastered.

Excellent RPG for the money! While this game does have ads and micro-transactions, the ads are limited to Kemco news and updates and only appear on the title screen when you press the NEWS button. As for micro-transactions, they are not really necessary and are only used to unlock more LIP (Legend of Ixtona Points) which you earn naturally from battles (3 per battle). The story, while not 100% compelling, is still great for what it is, and I've already grown attached to the cast of characters after only a few hours. The battles are really fun, and can be quite addicting! The game does support controllers (I use a keyboard) and can be played offline, which is great for if you want to play on a tablet during a long car trip. Overall, a great SRPG for the money. If you love JRPGs and want to delve into the SRPG sub-genre, this is a great first entry.

God artwork, decent translation for English subs, excellent gameplay and progression....and a very sudden a unexpected end of gameplay. Took me about 4 hours to beat the game.  I came in hoping for something like Tactics Ogre and Final Fantasy Tactics, and that's actually pretty much what I got. But....light. The skill progression is dumbed down, the game is so short, you don't even reach the 2nd job change for any characters before you hit the final battle unless you grind for no reason (because you don't need to, the game is a little too easy).  You can hire team members, but you don't need to, because as the story progresses, you get enough unique and interesting people the vanilla human fighter/mage/rogue people you can hire are boring and needless. You can't send any of the main storyline people off on their own to gather stuff, so you hire ONE person to do that, and you'll have all the people you can use at any one time.  It was a good game, but would have been a hell of a lot better if it wasn't so frustratingly short. If you're looking for an introductory game to turn-based tactical quad rps, try it out. But don't expect a challenge or have hours of gameplay.
